sentence = 'today is a  very nice day,but  we have to spend it in the lab.too   bad,no?'

  • Clean up: remove redundant spaces, capitalize the letters at the beginning of a sentence and after a punctuation sign

  • This kind of job is very common in programming (e.g. filling out online forms)

  • Let's consider a simpler version of this task: cleaning up a name user entered

The task

  • We are organising a party and asking everyone to enter their name in an online form we have created

  • A person enters their name, and we print a personalized welcome message

In [27]: 
# these lines display the form below, just to give you an idea of a "real" scenario of the task

Your name:

The task

  • We can assume that in most of the cases users will do what they are asked, but typos and mistakes still happen so we might see:

    _ivana (space in front of the name)

    ivana_ (space after the name)

    IVAna (mixed lowercase and uppercase letters)

  • Our task is to make sure that even when a user has typed a name with such mistakes, we still print a nice looking message:

    Hello Ivana

Let us (you ;) write a program which does that!

One possible solution...

In [29]: 
name = raw_input('What is your name? ')

clean_name = name.strip()
clean_name = clean_name.lower()
clean_name = clean_name.capitalize()

print 'Hello', clean_name

What is your name? ivaNA 
Hello Ivana

Cleaning up a name using a function

In [22]: 
def clean_up(text):
    clean_text = text.strip()
    clean_text = clean_text.lower()
    clean_text = clean_text.capitalize()
    
    return clean_text
In []: 
name = raw_input('What is your name?' )
surname = raw_input('What is your surname?' )
mothers_name = raw_input("What is your mother's name? ")
In [29]: 
clean_name = clean_up(name)
clean_surname = clean_up(surname)
clean_mothers_name = clean_up(mothers_name)
In [31]: 
print 'Hello,', clean_name, '(', clean_mothers_name, ')', clean_surname

Python functions

In [12]: 
def convert_euro_to_kuna(amount_euro):
    """
    Converts an amount in Euro (EUR) to Croatian kuna (HRK).
    Parameters:
        amount_euro: Amount of money in Euro
    Returns:
        amout_kuna: Amount of money in Kuna
    """
    amount_kuna = 0
    if amount_euro > 0:
        amount_kuna = amount_euro*7.65
    else:
        print 'Hey, I can only convert money if you have it!'
    
    return amount_kuna

money_ivana_takes_to_croatia = convert_euro_to_kuna(100)

Terminology to remember

  • Definition of a function vs. call of a function

  • Parameters and arguments

  • Return values

  • Docstring (inspect them with ? character in IPython)

Programming homework

  1. Create a file text_functions.py and write following functions inside:

    * `count_vowels`: returns the number of vowels in a given word, otherwise -1

* `remove_vowels`: returns a word with all the vowels removed AND the number of letters in a new word

  2. Now, create a new file called text.py in the same directory, containing the following lines:

In []: 
from text_functions import count_vowels, remove_vowels

sentence = 'Is it possible to understand this sentence even if the vowels are missing?'

nr_vowels = count_vowels(sentence)
print 'This sentence has:', nr_vowels, ' vowels'

new_sentence, length = remove_vowels(sentence)
print 'If we remove them, we are still left with ', length, ' letters'
print new_sentence
  • Analyse this program and explain it line by line by writing comments in the code
